          topic: "Revision",
          weeks: 3,
          content: "<strong>Grade 12 Life Sciences — Full Revision Guide</strong><br><br>This revision section covers all four terms of the Grade 12 Life Sciences CAPS curriculum. Use this as a checklist and summary to prepare for your final examinations.<br><br><strong>Paper 1 Topics (2.5 hours, 150 marks)</strong><br><br><strong>1. Meiosis</strong><ul><li>Stages of meiosis I and II — be able to draw and describe each phase.</li><li>Crossing over, independent assortment, and random fertilisation as sources of genetic variation.</li><li>Comparison between mitosis and meiosis (table format).</li><li>Non-disjunction and chromosomal abnormalities (Down syndrome, Turner syndrome, Klinefelter syndrome).</li></ul><strong>2. Genetics and Inheritance</strong><ul><li>Key terminology: gene, allele, locus, genotype, phenotype, homozygous, heterozygous, dominant, recessive.</li><li>Monohybrid crosses — complete dominance, incomplete dominance, co-dominance.</li><li>Dihybrid crosses — 9:3:3:1 ratio and deviations.</li><li>Blood groups (ABO and Rh factor) — co-dominance and multiple alleles.</li><li>Sex-linked inheritance — haemophilia, colour blindness.</li><li>Pedigree diagram interpretation.</li></ul><strong>3. DNA: The Code of Life</strong><ul><li>Nucleotide structure and DNA double helix.</li><li>Complementary base pairing (A-T, G-C).</li><li>DNA replication — helicase, DNA polymerase, semi-conservative replication.</li><li>Protein synthesis — transcription (in nucleus) and translation (at ribosome).</li><li>mRNA, tRNA, codons, anticodons, amino acids, polypeptide chains.</li><li>Using a codon table.</li></ul><strong>4. Human Reproduction</strong><ul><li>Male reproductive system — testes, epididymis, vas deferens, seminal vesicles, prostate, urethra, penis.</li><li>Female reproductive system — ovaries, Fallopian tubes, uterus, cervix, vagina.</li><li>Menstrual cycle — FSH, LH, oestrogen, progesterone; follicular phase, ovulation, luteal phase.</li><li>Fertilisation, implantation, placenta functions, pregnancy trimesters.</li><li>Birth — role of oxytocin, positive feedback.</li><li>Contraception methods and STIs (especially HIV/AIDS in SA context).</li></ul><strong>5. Responding to the Environment — Humans (Nervous System)</strong><ul><li>CNS and PNS, somatic and autonomic nervous systems.</li><li>Neuron structure — cell body, dendrites, axon, myelin sheath, nodes of Ranvier.</li><li>Synapse and synaptic transmission.</li><li>Reflex arc with example.</li><li>Brain structure — cerebrum, cerebellum, medulla oblongata, hypothalamus.</li><li>Diseases: Alzheimer's, Parkinson's.</li></ul><strong>6. Endocrine System and Homeostasis</strong><ul><li>Negative feedback — thermoregulation and blood glucose regulation.</li><li>Insulin, glucagon, adrenaline, thyroxine, TSH.</li><li>Diabetes Type 1 vs Type 2.</li><li>Positive feedback — oxytocin during birth.</li></ul><strong>Paper 2 Topics (2.5 hours, 150 marks)</strong><br><br><strong>7. DNA — Meiosis — Genetics Link</strong><ul><li>Paper 2 may include application questions linking DNA structure, replication, protein synthesis, meiosis, and genetics.</li></ul><strong>8. Evolution</strong><ul><li>Evidence: fossils, biogeography, comparative anatomy (homologous, analogous, vestigial structures), embryology, molecular evidence.</li><li>Natural selection — step-by-step explanation.</li><li>Speciation — allopatric (geographical isolation) and sympatric.</li><li>Lamarck vs Darwin.</li><li>Punctuated equilibrium vs gradualism.</li></ul><strong>9. Human Evolution</strong><ul><li>Evidence for common ancestry with African apes (DNA, chromosomes, anatomy).</li><li>Differences between humans and apes (bipedalism, brain size, foramen magnum, jaw, pelvis, spine).</li><li>Key species: Australopithecus africanus, A. sediba, Homo habilis, Homo erectus, Homo sapiens, Homo naledi.</li><li>Out of Africa hypothesis vs Multi-regional hypothesis.</li><li>Cradle of Humankind sites — Sterkfontein, Swartkrans, Malapa, Rising Star.</li><li>Cultural evolution — tools, fire, agriculture, language.</li></ul><strong>10. Responding to the Environment — Plants</strong><ul><li>Plant hormones: auxins, gibberellins, abscisic acid, cytokinins, ethylene — functions and commercial uses.</li><li>Tropisms: phototropism, geotropism, thigmotropism — mechanisms involving auxin.</li><li>Nastic movements vs tropisms.</li><li>Photoperiodism: short-day, long-day, day-neutral plants; phytochrome (Pr and Pfr).</li></ul><strong>11. Human Impact on the Environment</strong><ul><li>Biodiversity — three levels, SA hotspots, importance.</li><li>Threats: habitat destruction, pollution, overexploitation, invasive alien species.</li><li>Eutrophication — step by step.</li><li>Greenhouse effect and enhanced greenhouse effect.</li><li>Climate change causes and consequences.</li><li>Ozone depletion and the Montreal Protocol.</li><li>Conservation: protected areas, legislation (NEMA, NEMBA, CITES), sustainable development, community-based conservation.</li></ul><strong>Exam Strategy Tips</strong><br><br><ul><li><strong>Paper 1:</strong> Focus on Genetics (crosses take time — practise Punnett squares), Reproduction (hormone graphs), Nervous and Endocrine systems (diagrams and processes).</li><li><strong>Paper 2:</strong> Focus on Evolution (essay questions are common), Human Evolution (fossil comparisons), Environmental Studies (application and data interpretation).</li><li>Read each question carefully — underline key instructional words (describe, explain, compare, discuss, evaluate).</li><li>Use labelled diagrams wherever possible — they earn marks.</li><li>For long questions (essay-type), plan your answer before writing. Include an introduction, body with clear paragraphs, and conclusion.</li><li>Time management: Paper 1 and Paper 2 are each 2.5 hours for 150 marks — aim for about 1 minute per mark.</li><li>Practise past exam papers (DBE papers from previous years) — these are the best revision tool.</li><li>Make summary tables comparing: mitosis vs meiosis, DNA vs RNA, nervous vs endocrine system, Type 1 vs Type 2 diabetes, allopatric vs sympatric speciation.</li></ul>",
