          topic: "Revision",
          weeks: 4,
          content: "<strong>REVISION — Grade 12 CAT Final Exam Preparation</strong><br><br><strong>Exam Structure (CAPS):</strong><br>CAT has TWO papers and a PAT:<br><br><strong>Paper 1 — Theory (3 hours, 150 marks):</strong><br>Covers all theory content: System Technologies, Internet &amp; WWW, Information Management, Social Implications. Questions include multiple choice, matching, true/false, short answers, and longer scenario-based questions.<br><br><strong>Paper 2 — Practical (3 hours, 150 marks):</strong><br>Hands-on exam using a computer. Includes:<ul><li>Word Processing (~40 marks)</li><li>Spreadsheets (~55 marks)</li><li>Databases &amp; SQL (~40 marks)</li><li>HTML/Web Design (~15 marks)</li></ul><strong>Theory Topics Summary:</strong><br><br><strong>System Technologies:</strong><br>• Hardware: input, output, processing (CPU), memory (RAM, ROM, cache), storage (HDD, SSD, cloud)<br>• Software: system vs application, open-source vs proprietary<br>• Data representation: bits, bytes, ASCII, Unicode<br>• Ports and connectivity: USB, HDMI, Bluetooth, Wi-Fi, Ethernet<br><br><strong>Internet &amp; WWW:</strong><br>• Internet vs WWW, ISPs, connection types (fibre, ADSL, mobile data)<br>• Web browsers, URLs, search techniques<br>• Email (SMTP, POP3, IMAP), CC vs BCC<br>• Internet safety: HTTPS, phishing, malware, firewalls, 2FA<br><br><strong>Information Management:</strong><br>• Data → Information → Knowledge<br>• Evaluating sources (CRAAP test)<br>• Plagiarism and referencing<br>• File management and backups<br><br><strong>Social Implications:</strong><br>• Ethics: copyright, piracy, IP, Creative Commons<br>• Health: RSI, eye strain, ergonomics<br>• Environment: e-waste, green computing<br>• Security: malware types, protection measures<br>• Law: POPIA, ECT Act, Cybercrimes Act<br>• Digital divide<br><br><strong>Practical Skills Summary:</strong><br><br><strong>Word Processing:</strong><br>• Formatting (character, paragraph, page), styles, TOC<br>• Mail merge (data source, merge fields)<br>• Track changes, comments, find &amp; replace<br>• Tables, graphics, columns, sections, page/section breaks<br><br><strong>Spreadsheets:</strong><br>• Cell referencing (relative, absolute, mixed)<br>• Functions: SUM, AVERAGE, MIN, MAX, COUNT, COUNTA, IF (nested), AND, OR, VLOOKUP, COUNTIF, SUMIF, LEFT, RIGHT, MID, LEN, UPPER, LOWER, CONCATENATE, ROUND, INT, TODAY, YEAR, MONTH, DAY<br>• Charts: column, bar, line, pie, scatter — choosing appropriate types<br>• Conditional formatting, data validation, sorting, filtering<br>• What-if analysis (Goal Seek)<br><br><strong>Databases:</strong><br>• Tables, fields, records, data types, primary/foreign keys<br>• Relationships and referential integrity<br>• SQL: SELECT, FROM, WHERE, ORDER BY, GROUP BY, HAVING, JOIN<br>• Aggregate functions: COUNT, SUM, AVG, MAX, MIN<br>• LIKE, AND, OR, BETWEEN, IN, calculated fields, aliases (AS)<br>• Forms (data input) and Reports (formatted output)<br><br><strong>HTML:</strong><br>• Document structure: html, head, title, body<br>• Tags: headings, paragraphs, lists, links, images, tables, forms<br>• CSS: inline, internal, external; selectors; common properties<br><br><strong>Revision Strategy:</strong><ul><li><strong>Week 1:</strong> Theory revision — System Technologies and Internet. Make summary notes.</li><li><strong>Week 2:</strong> Theory revision — Information Management and Social Implications. Do past paper theory questions.</li><li><strong>Week 3:</strong> Practical revision — Word processing, Spreadsheets. Practice past practical papers.</li><li><strong>Week 4:</strong> Practical revision — Databases/SQL, HTML. Full past papers under timed conditions.</li></ul><strong>Exam Day Tips:</strong><ul><li><strong>Theory paper:</strong> Read scenarios carefully. Many questions are context-based. Use correct CAT terminology. Define terms precisely.</li><li><strong>Practical paper:</strong> Save your work frequently (Ctrl+S). Read each instruction carefully — marks are lost by skipping small details. If you get stuck on a question, move on and come back later. Check your formulas and SQL queries produce reasonable results.</li><li>Time management: allocate time per section based on marks available.</li><li>For spreadsheet formulas, ensure correct syntax and cell references.</li><li>For SQL, watch for common errors: missing semicolons, incorrect field names, forgetting quotes around text values.</li></ul>",
