          topic: "Civil Society Resistance (1950s–1970s)",
          weeks: 4,
          content: "<strong>Civil Society Resistance 1950s–1970s — Grade 12 CAPS History</strong><br><br><strong>1. The Defiance Campaign (1952)</strong><br><ul><li>Launched by the <strong>ANC</strong> and <strong>South African Indian Congress (SAIC)</strong> against unjust apartheid laws</li><li>Strategy of <strong>non-violent civil disobedience</strong> — volunteers deliberately broke apartheid laws (using whites-only facilities, entering locations without permits, breaking curfew)</li><li>Led by <strong>Nelson Mandela</strong> (volunteer-in-chief) and <strong>Walter Sisulu</strong></li><li>Over <strong>8 500 volunteers</strong> were arrested</li><li>ANC membership grew from 7 000 to over 100 000</li><li>Government responded with harsher laws and banning orders</li><li><strong>Significance:</strong> showed mass resistance was possible; built alliances across racial groups; raised international awareness</li></ul><br><strong>2. The Freedom Charter (1955)</strong><br><ul><li>Adopted at the <strong>Congress of the People</strong> in Kliptown, Soweto, on 26 June 1955</li><li>Organised by the <strong>Congress Alliance</strong>: ANC, SAIC, Coloured People&#39;s Congress, Congress of Democrats, SACTU</li><li>Thousands of volunteers collected demands from ordinary people across South Africa</li><li><strong>Key demands:</strong> equal rights for all, sharing of wealth, land reform, free education, workers&#39; rights, housing for all</li><li>The government broke up the gathering and later charged 156 leaders with <strong>treason</strong> (Treason Trial 1956–1961 — all acquitted)</li><li><strong>Significance:</strong> became the foundational document of the anti-apartheid movement; influenced the 1996 Constitution</li></ul><br><strong>3. Sharpeville Massacre (21 March 1960)</strong><br><ul><li>The <strong>PAC (Pan Africanist Congress)</strong>, led by <strong>Robert Sobukwe</strong>, organised a campaign against pass laws</li><li>Thousands of unarmed protesters gathered at Sharpeville police station without their passes</li><li>Police opened fire on the crowd — <strong>69 people killed</strong>, over 180 wounded, many shot in the back</li><li>Government declared a <strong>State of Emergency</strong>; <strong>banned the ANC and PAC</strong></li><li>ANC formed <strong>Umkhonto we Sizwe (MK)</strong> — the armed wing — in December 1961, led by Nelson Mandela</li><li>PAC formed <strong>POQO</strong> as its armed wing</li><li><strong>Significance:</strong> turning point — shift from non-violent to armed resistance; international condemnation; 21 March is now Human Rights Day in South Africa</li></ul><br><strong>4. Rivonia Trial (1963–1964)</strong><br><ul><li>Police raided <strong>Liliesleaf Farm</strong> in Rivonia, Johannesburg, and arrested top MK leaders</li><li><strong>Nelson Mandela</strong> (already imprisoned), <strong>Walter Sisulu</strong>, <strong>Govan Mbeki</strong>, <strong>Ahmed Kathrada</strong>, <strong>Denis Goldberg</strong>, <strong>Raymond Mhlaba</strong>, <strong>Andrew Mlangeni</strong>, and <strong>Elias Motsoaledi</strong> were charged with sabotage</li><li>Mandela&#39;s famous speech from the dock: <em>\"I have cherished the ideal of a democratic and free society... it is an ideal for which I am prepared to die\"</em></li><li>Eight accused sentenced to <strong>life imprisonment</strong> on Robben Island</li><li><strong>Significance:</strong> decapitated the liberation movement&#39;s leadership inside South Africa; struggle continued from exile; Mandela became a global symbol of resistance</li></ul><br><strong>5. Black Consciousness Movement (BCM)</strong><br><ul><li>Emerged in the late 1960s when liberation movements were banned and leaders imprisoned or in exile</li><li>Founded by <strong>Steve Biko</strong> while a medical student at the University of Natal (Black Section)</li><li>Established <strong>SASO (South African Students&#39; Organisation)</strong> in 1968</li><li><strong>Core philosophy:</strong> Black people must liberate themselves psychologically before they can be liberated politically; reject white liberal paternalism; pride in black identity, history, and culture</li><li><strong>\"Black man, you are on your own\"</strong> — rallying call for self-reliance</li><li>Influenced community programmes: literacy, healthcare, self-help projects (Black Community Programmes)</li><li><strong>Steve Biko</strong> was banned, arrested multiple times, and died in police detention on <strong>12 September 1977</strong> — beaten by security police</li><li><strong>Significance:</strong> revived resistance among black youth; inspired the Soweto Uprising; Biko became a martyr for the anti-apartheid cause</li></ul><br><strong>6. Soweto Uprising (16 June 1976)</strong><br><ul><li>Students in Soweto protested against the compulsory use of <strong>Afrikaans as a medium of instruction</strong> in black schools</li><li>Approximately <strong>20 000 students</strong> marched peacefully</li><li>Police responded with <strong>tear gas and live ammunition</strong></li><li><strong>Hector Pieterson</strong> (aged 12) was among the first to be killed — the iconic photograph of his body being carried became a global symbol</li><li>Uprising spread across the country — <strong>over 575 people killed</strong> by the end of 1976</li><li>Thousands of young people fled South Africa to join MK and the ANC in exile</li><li><strong>Significance:</strong> re-energised the anti-apartheid struggle; brought international attention and condemnation; 16 June is now <strong>Youth Day</strong> in South Africa</li></ul><br><strong>Exam Tips:</strong><ul><li>Know the chronological sequence of events and how each led to the next</li><li>Understand the shift from non-violent resistance to armed struggle</li><li>Be able to discuss the role of key individuals: Mandela, Sobukwe, Biko, Sisulu</li><li>Practise source-based questions using photographs (Sharpeville, Hector Pieterson), speeches (Mandela&#39;s dock speech), and documents (Freedom Charter)</li><li>Link civil society resistance to the broader apartheid context</li></ul>",
