          topic: "Apartheid South Africa (1960s–1980s)",
          weeks: 3,
          content: "<strong>Apartheid South Africa 1960s–1980s — Grade 12 CAPS History</strong><br><br><strong>1. The Apartheid State Tightens Control (1960s)</strong><br><ul><li>After Sharpeville (1960), the government banned the ANC and PAC and declared a State of Emergency</li><li><strong>Increased security legislation:</strong> Sabotage Act (1962), General Law Amendment Act (90-day detention without trial), Terrorism Act (1967)</li><li><strong>Bureau of State Security (BOSS)</strong> established to monitor and suppress opposition</li><li>Most resistance leaders imprisoned (Robben Island) or forced into exile</li><li>South Africa became a <strong>republic</strong> in 1961 and left the Commonwealth</li></ul><br><strong>2. P.W. Botha and the Total Strategy (1978–1989)</strong><br><br><strong>P.W. Botha</strong> became Prime Minister in 1978 (later State President). He believed South Africa faced a <strong>\"total onslaught\"</strong> from communism and anti-apartheid forces, requiring a <strong>\"total strategy\"</strong> — a combination of military force and limited reforms.<br><br><strong>Military Actions:</strong><ul><li>South African Defence Force (SADF) launched cross-border raids into Angola, Mozambique, Lesotho, Botswana, and Zimbabwe</li><li>Destabilisation of neighbouring states — supporting rebel movements (RENAMO in Mozambique, UNITA in Angola)</li><li>Massive military spending and development of nuclear weapons (secretly)</li></ul><strong>Limited Reforms:</strong><ul><li><strong>Tricameral Parliament (1983):</strong> created three houses of parliament — for Whites, Coloureds, and Indians — but <strong>excluded Black Africans entirely</strong></li><li>Some petty apartheid laws relaxed (mixed sport, some desegregated facilities)</li><li>Labour reforms — black trade unions legalised</li><li>These reforms were seen as attempts to co-opt Coloured and Indian communities while maintaining white supremacy</li></ul><br><strong>3. The United Democratic Front (UDF) and Mass Mobilisation</strong><br><ul><li><strong>UDF</strong> launched on 20 August 1983 in Mitchell&#39;s Plain, Cape Town — a broad coalition of over <strong>600 organisations</strong> (civic associations, churches, trade unions, student groups, women&#39;s organisations)</li><li>Formed specifically to oppose the <strong>Tricameral Parliament</strong> and the Black Local Authorities Act</li><li>Leaders included <strong>Allan Boesak</strong>, <strong>Albertina Sisulu</strong>, <strong>Archie Gumede</strong></li><li>Aligned with the ANC&#39;s Freedom Charter but operated legally inside South Africa</li><li><strong>Mass mobilisation tactics:</strong> boycotts (consumer, school, rent), stay-aways, marches, defiance of apartheid laws</li><li>Township uprisings spread across South Africa from 1984 — youth, workers, and communities resisted</li></ul><br><strong>4. States of Emergency (1985 and 1986)</strong><br><ul><li>Government declared a <strong>partial State of Emergency</strong> in July 1985 and a <strong>nationwide State of Emergency</strong> in June 1986</li><li>Gave security forces sweeping powers: detention without trial, censorship of media, banning of organisations</li><li>Over <strong>30 000 people detained</strong> without trial between 1986 and 1989</li><li>Many activists tortured, killed, or disappeared</li><li>Despite repression, resistance continued and intensified</li></ul><br><strong>5. International Sanctions and Disinvestment</strong><br><ul><li><strong>Sports boycott:</strong> South Africa banned from the Olympics (1964) and most international sport</li><li><strong>Cultural boycott:</strong> artists, musicians, and academics refused to perform or work in South Africa</li><li><strong>Economic sanctions:</strong> many countries imposed trade restrictions; <strong>USA Comprehensive Anti-Apartheid Act (1986)</strong></li><li><strong>Disinvestment:</strong> international companies pulled out of South Africa (Barclays Bank, IBM, Coca-Cola, General Motors)</li><li><strong>Financial crisis:</strong> Chase Manhattan Bank refused to roll over South African loans in 1985 — rand collapsed</li><li><strong>Arms embargo:</strong> UN mandatory arms embargo (1977)</li><li><strong>Anti-apartheid movements worldwide:</strong> Free Mandela Campaign, concerts (Mandela 70th Birthday Concert at Wembley, 1988)</li></ul><strong>Impact of Sanctions:</strong><ul><li>Increased economic pressure on the apartheid government</li><li>Isolated South Africa diplomatically and culturally</li><li>Contributed to the government&#39;s decision to negotiate (along with military stalemate and internal resistance)</li></ul><br><strong>6. The Role of the Church and Civil Society</strong><br><ul><li><strong>Archbishop Desmond Tutu:</strong> won the Nobel Peace Prize (1984); called for sanctions and non-violent resistance</li><li><strong>South African Council of Churches (SACC):</strong> opposed apartheid on moral grounds</li><li><strong>COSATU (Congress of South African Trade Unions, 1985):</strong> organised massive stay-aways and strikes; allied with UDF and ANC</li><li><strong>End Conscription Campaign:</strong> white South Africans opposing compulsory military service</li></ul><br><strong>Exam Tips:</strong><ul><li>Understand the concept of \"total strategy\" — both military and reform components</li><li>Be able to explain why the Tricameral Parliament was rejected by most South Africans</li><li>Know the role of the UDF, COSATU, and the church in mass resistance</li><li>Discuss the impact of international sanctions — economic, sporting, cultural, diplomatic</li><li>Practise source-based questions using photographs, newspaper articles, and political cartoons from the 1980s</li></ul>",
